(150, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/court-order-stops-eviction-of-alotau-settlers/', 'Latest News', ' Court order stops eviction of Alotau settlers ', '   BY THIERRY LEPANI A COURT order has been successfully obtained to stop the eviction of residents of the 26 different settlements, compounds and villages in Alotau. The National Court order was handed down yesterday by Justice Collin Makail which stays the eviction exercise currently underway pending the determination of the substantive matter. The order states “The current eviction and repatriation exercise being under taken by the Defendants and their agents and employees in and around Alotau town is stayed or injuncted. “Any direction instruction, and orders by the First, Second and Third Defendants to repatriate or evict the plaintiffs and others from their current homes in the 26 settlements, compounds and villages  is stayed or injuncted”. The 26 affected settlements concerned are: Power House/AOG Habours Rabaraba Goodenough Watertank Goilanai (Customary Land) Gawa Hideaway Duau Mobil/IPL 1 Mobil/IPL 2 Kewa Yabwau PTB NBC Red Hill Denewa (Customary Land) Kuboma Masurina Niugini Kitava (Customary Land) Siona 1 and 2 (Customary Land) Musa (Customary Land) Suau (Customary Land) Daga (Customary Land) Morima KB (Customary Land) Hihiyaola (customary land) Justice Makail also ordered that the defendants, which include the police, provincial government and Alotau authorities, from taking any step whatsoever to evict or repatriate any of the plaintiffs from their current homes. “Threatening, harassing and intimidating in whatsoever manner the plaintiffs and their families” was also restrained. Also, the defendants are restrained from entering the homes and premises of the plaintiffs to evict or repatriate the plaintiffs in the absence of any orders or warrants issued by a court of competent jurisdiction. The matter is adjourned to Tuesday July 6 for inter partes hearing. The order takes place forthwith. The plaintiffs acting on behalf of the settlers are Steven Paul Nesai, Paulus Mumna and Steven Luguna, who are represented by Baniyamai Lawyers.     ', NULL, NULL),
(151, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/dei-council-to-benefit-from-road-after-40-years-of-neglect/', 'National News', ' Dei Council to benefit from road after 40 years of neglect ', '   BY GORETHY KENNETH WALKING for hours and many kilometers will now be a thing of the past for the population of Dei Council in Western Highlands. That electorate, on many occasions has been known for being a war zone area. For over 40 years, they have not had the luxury of catching a vehicle at their doorstep – because there has been no proper roads. The population that will now benefit from the Eng-Ambra 20 kilometre road said in the past, they would walk for hours to the central place with their market produce, their coffee bags and other essential matters in order to catch a PMV or a truck to go to Mt Hagen town for
business. “It was very tough for us, we have been doing tough for the last 20 to 30 years walking long distances for more than one or two hours just to get or catch a PMV to town to either sell our coffee, take our market produce to the main market, or go to town to do other business and for us teachers, to attend to important meetings and do school runs,” Headmaster for the Eng Kal Primary School David Kunai
said. He said the school runs and operations were also very affected over the years but this will now be a thing of the past. They can now wake up to a bus service right at their door step as a 20km road network has been built, sealed and about to be completed by end of this year. Dei Council MP Wesley Nukundj has told Post-Courier that under the K10 million Public Investment Program (PIP) funds this has done wonders for the people – the complete 5.5 km Eng-Ambra road sealed, another 8 kilometer being graded and sealing soon to start including the rest in progress and should be completed by end of the year. Chief Executive Officer of the Dei Council Batamai Tipi also said that after so many years of very bad road system the 3.5km sealed road and the rest of the 17km graded road awaiting sealing will now benefit thousands of people in the area including public servants, farmers, business SMEs, coffee buyers and farmers, students and teachers from a high school and five primary schools, mothers and the public at large. The first phase of grading and sealing of the 3.5 km stretch of the road has been done, the next phase of grading of the remaining kilometers now underway and sealing should also be carried out. Local Kaiaworks Road Company is carrying out the contract.   ', NULL, NULL),
