(153, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/pm-to-launch-alternative-highlands-highway/', 'National News', ' PM to launch alternative Highlands Highway ', '   BY ISAAC LIRI THE 64km Dunantina-Ramu Highway in Kesavaka, Henganofi district of Eastern Highlands Province was announced yesterday as an alternate Highlands Highway. The road once completed in the future will give options to travellers coming from the upper Highlands and those coming from the coastal provinces of Madang and Morobe to take the route. The launch was officiated by Prime Minister James Marape, Works Minister Michael Nali, Minister for National Planning and Monitoring Renbo Paita, Eastern Highlands Governor Peter Numu, Henganofi MP Robert Atiyafa, Mining Minister Johnson Tuke, Minister for Petroleum Saki Soloma, Goroka MP Aiye Tambua, Works Secretary David Wereh and others. Hundreds both young and old gathered at Kesavakato witness what was described as a historical event to hear the government talk of how the road will benefit the people of Henganofi and the Highlands and Momase regions. Mr Marape told the people of Kesavaka constructing roads is a priority in which his government has embarked on therefore, commended Mr Atiyafa for working tirelessly to see that the project proceeds. He said the government through the Works Department have been working on roads under a program which he referred to as Connect PNG with the aim of connecting parts of country especially in rural areas with roads. He also added that the government is spending billions on constructing and maintaining roads.
Therefore the people must allow development to take place because the road will benefit them now and in the future. Mr Nali also encouraged the people of Henganofi to change their mindsets and prepare to welcome the development of the road. He said under the Asian Development Bank, the Dunantina-Ramu road will proceed on as trench one meaning that the project implementation is just around the corner. Both Mr Numu and Mr Atiyafa thanked the Prime Minister and State Ministers for visiting Dunantina and they described the place once known as back page to become a front page meaning that business activities and other government services such as health and education will flourish following the opening of the alternate highway.   ', NULL, NULL),
