(162, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/hong-kong-police-arrests-apple-daily-newspaper-editor-in-chief/', 'World News', ' Hong Kong police arrests Apple Daily newspaper editor-in-chief ', '   HONG KONG: Hong Kong’s national security police have arrested the editor-in-chief and four other directors of the Apple Daily newspaper in early morning raids involving hundreds of officers, over their role in the publication of dozens of articles alleged to be part of a conspiracy to collude with foreign forces. The city’s security chief, John Lee, accused those arrested of using “journalistic work as a tool to endanger national security”, and issued a chilling warning to residents and other media. “Normal journalists are different from these people,” Lee said. “Please keep a distance from them.” The police force’s national security department said the five had been arrested on suspicion of collusion with a foreign country or with external elements to endanger national security, through articles which police said called for sanctions to be imposed on Hong Kong and mainland China. All were arrested at their homes, at around 7am. Police also searched Apple Daily’s newsroom and its offices, saying the warrant covered “the power of searching and seizure of journalistic materials”. “The operation, still ongoing, aims at gathering evidence for a case of suspected contravention of the national security law,” it said. Those arrested were named by Apple Daily as editor-in-chief, Ryan Law; the chief executive officer, Cheung Kim-hung; the chief operating officer, Chow Tat-kuen; the deputy chief editor, Chan Puiman; and the chief executive editor, Cheung Chi-wai. Police also froze HK$18m (US $2.3m) in assets of three companies, Apple Daily Limited, Apple Daily Printing Limited and AD Internet Limited. Parent company, Next Digital, announced the suspension of trading in its shares before markets opened on Thursday. The police operation is a significant escalation in the government’s moves to stifle Hong Kong’s press, of which the pro-democracy tabloid was widely considered to be a primary target. Senior superintendent Steve Li Kwai-wah, the head of the police’s national security division, said there was “very strong evidence that the questionable articles played a very crucial part in the conspiracy, which provided ammunition for foreign countries, institutions and organisations to impose sanctions”, adding that those arrested played “a very important role” in their publication. -The Guardian   ', NULL, NULL),
(163, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/dei-council-to-benefit-from-road-after-40-years-of-neglect/', 'National News', ' Dei Council to benefit from road after 40 years of neglect ', '   BY GORETHY KENNETH WALKING for hours and many kilometers will now be a thing of the past for the population of Dei Council in Western Highlands. That electorate, on many occasions has been known for being a war zone area. For over 40 years, they have not had the luxury of catching a vehicle at their doorstep – because there has been no proper roads. The population that will now benefit from the Eng-Ambra 20 kilometre road said in the past, they would walk for hours to the central place with their market produce, their coffee bags and other essential matters in order to catch a PMV or a truck to go to Mt Hagen town for
business. “It was very tough for us, we have been doing tough for the last 20 to 30 years walking long distances for more than one or two hours just to get or catch a PMV to town to either sell our coffee, take our market produce to the main market, or go to town to do other business and for us teachers, to attend to important meetings and do school runs,” Headmaster for the Eng Kal Primary School David Kunai
said. He said the school runs and operations were also very affected over the years but this will now be a thing of the past. They can now wake up to a bus service right at their door step as a 20km road network has been built, sealed and about to be completed by end of this year. Dei Council MP Wesley Nukundj has told Post-Courier that under the K10 million Public Investment Program (PIP) funds this has done wonders for the people – the complete 5.5 km Eng-Ambra road sealed, another 8 kilometer being graded and sealing soon to start including the rest in progress and should be completed by end of the year. Chief Executive Officer of the Dei Council Batamai Tipi also said that after so many years of very bad road system the 3.5km sealed road and the rest of the 17km graded road awaiting sealing will now benefit thousands of people in the area including public servants, farmers, business SMEs, coffee buyers and farmers, students and teachers from a high school and five primary schools, mothers and the public at large. The first phase of grading and sealing of the 3.5 km stretch of the road has been done, the next phase of grading of the remaining kilometers now underway and sealing should also be carried out. Local Kaiaworks Road Company is carrying out the contract.   ', NULL, NULL),
(164, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/png-needs-more-banks-pidik/', 'Business', ' PNG needs more banks: Pidik ', '   BY MAXINE KAMUS More commercial banks are needed in Papua New Guinea, says Bank of PNG assistant governor Ellison Pidik. Mr Pidik said as PNG is an emerging economy with a growing population and a market that is expanding at a faster rate than ever before, these indicates that PNG needs new players to enter into the banking space. He said in order to have balance in the market BPNG is welcoming other banks from overseas to come and operate and provide service to the growing population. “PNG banking space needs balance, it needs international banks to enter and operate in the country as currently we have four major banks that are operating at the commercial level,” Mr Pidik said. “We have four commercial banks in PNG financial sector with other deposit taking institutes that include 21 savings and loan societies and 10 licensed financial institutions. “With BSP as the largest in the country with 35 branches throughout the country and in six countries, BSP currently services over 650,000 business banking customers and with our fast growing population the banking sector needs more banks to enter,” Mr Pidik said. He said PNG needs banks that are listed on the stock exchanges, like Kina Bank and BSP who was recently listed on the stock exchanges in Australia. This is good as both are local and international banks although they are both domicile locally. Mr Pidik said the central bank is now looking at investors around the world and is also inviting other financial institutions operating to look at how they can merge something bigger that can qualify for a banking license similar to what the Teachers Savings and Loan Society (TISA) has done to apply for a banking license to operate as a commercial bank. He said TISA has applied specifically for a commercial banking license, which BPNG has assessed and identified a number of important priorities that BPNG thinks TISA should look into before BPNG go through completing the assessment of the license. Mr Pidik said, BPNG has met with the board and management of TISA and asked them to look into areas like prerequisites that they have to have in place before the assessment will be completed.   ', NULL, NULL),
(165, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/thoughts-of-jokadi-to-inspire-hunters-this-weekend/', 'Sports', ' Thoughts of Jokadi to inspire Hunters this weekend ', '   SP PNG Hunters will play for their teammate Jokadi Bire when they step into an NRL arena for Sunday’s much-awaited Intrust Super Cup clash with Burleigh Bears. The game will be played at Cbus Super Stadium on the Gold Coast as a curtain-raiser to the NRL clash between the Titans and Manly Sea Eagles. The Hunters would have loved Bire to have joined them in the backline however he will be at a Gold Coast hospital where he continues to recover from surgery on Tuesday night. Bire would not be out of place in the NRL arena with the fast feet and power that brought him a try in last Saturday’s clash with Norths Devils at Bishop Park. He flashed off his left foot and surged past Broncos hooker Danny Levi for an important try. Bire’s position in Sunday’s team will be taken by Norman Brown, who has overcome injury and moves from fullback to centre, while captain Ila Alu has recovered from a head knock to take his place. Hunters coach Matt Church said the two changes were another sign of the stability returning to selections in time for the second half of the season. “We’ve had to make two changes this week but otherwise we’re happy to have a very similar team to last week as we continue to build combinations for this run towards the finals,” Church said. “It’s a thrill for our guys to play at this ground. Most of our players fell in love with the game crowded around a TV with villages full of people watching on. Every kid in PNG wishes to play in the stadiums where their heroes play.” This will be the Hunters’ first game at Cbus Super Stadium although Kumuls Wartovo Puara Jnr and Stanton Albert represented their country on the ground against Fiji in 2015. Luke Page also represented the Kumuls in that match but he will lead Burleigh on Sunday in only their second match at the ground – the Bears defeated the Tigers there in 2018. The Hunters have established a close rivalry with the Bears, winning seven of their 13 previous matches. They were on track for an eighth win in April this year before the Bears ran home late to claim a memorable Kokoda Cup clash at Pizzey Park. The Hunters are determined to win on Sunday before a mid-season bye ends another block of matches in this season’s competition. After the bye, the Hunters will have three consecutive games before one last week off before the run to the finals. The Hunters are on the verge of a big performance after testing heavyweights such as Norths, Redcliffe and Townsville Blackhawks in recent weeks with the enterprising play that has rivals on notice. Solo Wane’s length-of-the-field run last Saturday was among the highlights of the round, leaving the Devils in his wake as he scorched 100m down the sideline for a stirring try. The SP PNG Hunters to play Burleigh Bears at Cbus Super Stadium on Sunday June 20 at 1.30pm:  SP PNG HUNTERS: 1. Joe Joshua 2. Junior Rau. 3.Brandon Nima. 4. Norman Brown. 5. Solo Wane. 6. Ase Boas 7 Charlie Simon. 8. Stanton Albert. 9. Wartovo Puara Jnr. 10. Samuel Yegip 11. Emmanuel Waine 12. Keven Appo. 13. Ila Alu (c). Interchange: 14. Judah Rimbu. 15. Sylvester Namo 16. Mark Piti 17. Enock Maki. Coach: Matt Church. BURLEIGH BEARS: 1. Kurtis Rowe 2. Jonus Pearson. 3. Conor Carey 4. Allan Lockwood 5. Andre Niko 6. Tanah Boyd 7. Conner Toia 8. Luke Page 9. Pat Politoni 10. John Palavi 11. Lochlyn Sheldon 12. Hayden Schwass. 13. Sam Coster. Interchange: 14. Shallin Fuller 15. Reece Summer 16. Api Noema-Matenga. 17.  Jeff Lynch. Coach: Rick Stone. Match officials: Liam Kennedy, Jarrod Cole, Steve Kanowski.         ', NULL, NULL),
(166, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/ela-motors-opens-new-dealership/', 'Business', ' Ela Motors opens new dealership ', '   BY JANET KARI Ela Motors branch in Lae has opened its newest dealership at Malaita Street in town early this week. The new dealership contains a spacious showroom, an office space for sales and administration, a customer service section for spare parts, a large workshop, and service area for car wash, an adequate parking space and others. This new set up is specifically for the franchise of Toyota which includes Toyota vehicles, spare parts for this franchise and a large workshop specifically for the Toyota brand, while the other dealership at Milford Haven road deals with Yamaha and Hino. The new shop now adds to the current ones operating at Taraka and at Milford Haven Road, with most of its customer services areas set up in a COVID-19 protective manner.   ', NULL, NULL),
