orld Rankings as per their selection criteria. Currently in Monacoto participate in the Women’s World Rugby Sevens Repechage tournament from 19-20 June are the PNG Rugby 7s Women Team who will be looking to string some strong performances to advance past the pool stages. The PNG Rugby 7s Women’s team are optimistic of their chances to make it to the final and finish in the top two out of twelve nations to qualify for the Tokyo 2020 Olympic Games. A proud Team PNG’s Chef de Mission Tamzin Wardley to the Tokyo 2020 Olympics congratulated the Weightlifters for qualifying on merit as well as John Ume, Ryan Maskelyne and Judith Meauri who were granted tripartite invitation place and universality places respectively.           ', NULL, NULL),
(186, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/court-order-stops-eviction-of-alotau-settlers/', 'Latest News', ' Court order stops eviction of Alotau settlers ', '   BY THIERRY LEPANI A COURT order has been successfully obtained to stop the eviction of residents of the 26 different settlements, compounds and villages in Alotau. The National Court order was handed down yesterday by Justice Collin Makail which stays the eviction exercise currently underway pending the determination of the substantive matter. The order states “The current eviction and repatriation exercise being under taken by the Defendants and their agents and employees in and around Alotau town is stayed or injuncted. “Any direction instruction, and orders by the First, Second and Third Defendants to repatriate or evict the plaintiffs and others from their current homes in the 26 settlements, compounds and villages  is stayed or injuncted”. The 26 affected settlements concerned are: Power House/AOG Habours Rabaraba Goodenough Watertank Goilanai (Customary Land) Gawa Hideaway Duau Mobil/IPL 1 Mobil/IPL 2 Kewa Yabwau PTB NBC Red Hill Denewa (Customary Land) Kuboma Masurina Niugini Kitava (Customary Land) Siona 1 and 2 (Customary Land) Musa (Customary Land) Suau (Customary Land) Daga (Customary Land) Morima KB (Customary Land) Hihiyaola (customary land) Justice Makail also ordered that the defendants, which include the police, provincial government and Alotau authorities, from taking any step whatsoever to evict or repatriate any of the plaintiffs from their current homes. “Threatening, harassing and intimidating in whatsoever manner the plaintiffs and their families” was also restrained. Also, the defendants are restrained from entering the homes and premises of the plaintiffs to evict or repatriate the plaintiffs in the absence of any orders or warrants issued by a court of competent jurisdiction. The matter is adjourned to Tuesday July 6 for inter partes hearing. The order takes place forthwith. The plaintiffs acting on behalf of the settlers are Steven Paul Nesai, Paulus Mumna and Steven Luguna, who are represented by Baniyamai Lawyers.     ', NULL, NULL),
(187, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/pm-to-launch-alternative-highlands-highway/', 'National News', ' PM to launch alternative Highlands Highway ', '   BY ISAAC LIRI THE 64km Dunantina-Ramu Highway in Kesavaka, Henganofi district of Eastern Highlands Province was announced yesterday as an alternate Highlands Highway. The road once completed in the future will give options to travellers coming from the upper Highlands and those coming from the coastal provinces of Madang and Morobe to take the route. The launch was officiated by Prime Minister James Marape, Works Minister Michael Nali, Minister for National Planning and Monitoring Renbo Paita, Eastern Highlands Governor Peter Numu, Henganofi MP Robert Atiyafa, Mining Minister Johnson Tuke, Minister for Petroleum Saki Soloma, Goroka MP Aiye Tambua, Works Secretary David Wereh and others. Hundreds both young and old gathered at Kesavakato witness what was described as a historical event to hear the government talk of how the road will benefit the people of Henganofi and the Highlands and Momase regions. Mr Marape told the people of Kesavaka constructing roads is a priority in which his government has embarked on therefore, commended Mr Atiyafa for working tirelessly to see that the project proceeds. He said the government through the Works Department have been working on roads under a program which he referred to as Connect PNG with the aim of connecting parts of country especially in rural areas with roads. He also added that the government is spending billions on constructing and maintaining roads.
Therefore the people must allow development to take place because the road will benefit them now and in the future. Mr Nali also encouraged the people of Henganofi to change their mindsets and prepare to welcome the development of the road. He said under the Asian Development Bank, the Dunantina-Ramu road will proceed on as trench one meaning that the project implementation is just around the corner. Both Mr Numu and Mr Atiyafa thanked the Prime Minister and State Ministers for visiting Dunantina and they described the place once known as back page to become a front page meaning that business activities and other government services such as health and education will flourish following the opening of the alternate highway.   ', NULL, NULL),
(188, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/air-niugini-flights-to-cairns-still-suspended/', 'Business', ' Air Niugini flights to Cairns still suspended ', '   The Australian government has extended the suspension of international arrivals into Cairns until end of this month. This is in order to manage the risk of arriving passengers subsequently testing positive for COVID-19 during their stay in quarantine facilities. For the period from June 19- 30, flights from PNG to Cairns have therefore been cancelled. Passengers holding tickets for Cairns flights over this period should contact Air Niugini or their travel agent for rebooking options. Air Niugini continues to operate six services a week to Brisbane, and a weekly service to Sydney. Air Niugini regrets the inconvenience caused and appreciates its customers’ patience and understanding while it manages its way through these latest border restrictions.   ', NULL, NULL),
(189, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/wnb-government-partners-with-chamber-of-commerce/', 'National News', ' WNB government partners with Chamber of Commerce ', '   By NICOLE JOANNES The West New Britain Provincial Government is partnering with the Chamber of Commerce and Industry for the use of PSIP funds allocated to Kimbe police. They have entered a memorandum of agreement for the Chamber of Commerce to disburse the funds to service providers upon submissions presented by the police. The agreement provides the guidelines for the use of the K500,000 presented to chamber by the regional Member Sasindran Muthuvel. This agreement was signed by Provincial Administrator Williamson Hosea, President of the Chamber of Commerce and Industry Ian O’Hanlon and provincial police commander Januarius Vosivai. The focus areas for the funding include the maintenance of the ten new vehicles and firearms, information call centre setup, community policing and other operational areas like CID, intelligence, VHF radios and infrastructures among others. Mr Muthuvel said this will save police time to have access to the money instead of the long government process. He thanked the Chamber of Commerce for the partnership arrangement which has also gone down well with the police. Mr Muthuvel said this arrangement came about following the visit of Lands Minister and Member for Lae John Rosso last year. Mr Rosso had an audience with chamber, and they had agreed for this move to cut down on time and to improve the response time of the police that is aimed at improving law and order. Meanwhile the acting assistant commissioner of police for NGI Paul Kamuai has thanked the provincial government and the Chamber of Commerce for this partnership arrangement. He also thanked the MP for the funding assistance and assured that the money will be used for the intended purposes to improve law and order in the province. Mr Kamuai said the expenditure on the use of the funding will be provided by PPC Vosivai.   ', NULL, NULL),
(190, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/solomon-cup-attracts-50-teams-in-bialla/', 'Sports', ' Solomon Cup attracts 50 teams in Bialla ', '   Local resident in Bialla town West New Britain Andrew Solomon has pledged K50,000 for Solomon Cup which will run for 20 weeks as soccer (male teams – 18 & female teams – 12) and volleyball (eight male teams and 12 female teams) competition. Solomon said at this time when law and order issues are at its highest peak in West New Britain, he pledged his support to the youths (boys and girls) in Bialla town with these competitions. He said Bialla has created history and has potential to produce super stars like Marcus Bai in rugby league. He said he will officiate at another competition around July in Kabaiya LSS, Noau village, Lolobau Island, Silanga, Marapu and Ubai village in Bialla LLG with a similar financial support before moving into Mosa LLG, Hoskins LLG, Kimbe Urban LLG, Talasea LLG and Bali Witu LLG. Rugby league will soon start in all local level governments too. He met with Sports Minister Wesley Raminai last week to deliver an official invitation to officiate at the Solomon Cup grand finals in October and is expected to be accompanied by PNG Football Association president, PNG Volleyball Association president, PNGRFL chairman and PNG Sports Federation chief executive officer. There will also be a district games that will see sides selected from each LLG to compete for K200,000 in various sports. He said his priority games are rugby league, soccer, volleyball and basketball and developing raw talent onto professionals. He said his main focus is to support Team West New Britain prepare for PNG Games in Mendi, Southern Highlands Province that is expected to be held in November this year.     ', NULL, NULL),
