said. He said the school runs and operations were also very affected over the years but this will now be a thing of the past. They can now wake up to a bus service right at their door step as a 20km road network has been built, sealed and about to be completed by end of this year. Dei Council MP Wesley Nukundj has told Post-Courier that under the K10 million Public Investment Program (PIP) funds this has done wonders for the people – the complete 5.5 km Eng-Ambra road sealed, another 8 kilometer being graded and sealing soon to start including the rest in progress and should be completed by end of the year. Chief Executive Officer of the Dei Council Batamai Tipi also said that after so many years of very bad road system the 3.5km sealed road and the rest of the 17km graded road awaiting sealing will now benefit thousands of people in the area including public servants, farmers, business SMEs, coffee buyers and farmers, students and teachers from a high school and five primary schools, mothers and the public at large. The first phase of grading and sealing of the 3.5 km stretch of the road has been done, the next phase of grading of the remaining kilometers now underway and sealing should also be carried out. Local Kaiaworks Road Company is carrying out the contract.   ', NULL, NULL),
(200, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/court-order-stops-eviction-of-alotau-settlers/', 'Latest News', ' Court order stops eviction of Alotau settlers ', '   BY THIERRY LEPANI A COURT order has been successfully obtained to stop the eviction of residents of the 26 different settlements, compounds and villages in Alotau. The National Court order was handed down yesterday by Justice Collin Makail which stays the eviction exercise currently underway pending the determination of the substantive matter. The order states “The current eviction and repatriation exercise being under taken by the Defendants and their agents and employees in and around Alotau town is stayed or injuncted. “Any direction instruction, and orders by the First, Second and Third Defendants to repatriate or evict the plaintiffs and others from their current homes in the 26 settlements, compounds and villages  is stayed or injuncted”. The 26 affected settlements concerned are: Power House/AOG Habours Rabaraba Goodenough Watertank Goilanai (Customary Land) Gawa Hideaway Duau Mobil/IPL 1 Mobil/IPL 2 Kewa Yabwau PTB NBC Red Hill Denewa (Customary Land) Kuboma Masurina Niugini Kitava (Customary Land) Siona 1 and 2 (Customary Land) Musa (Customary Land) Suau (Customary Land) Daga (Customary Land) Morima KB (Customary Land) Hihiyaola (customary land) Justice Makail also ordered that the defendants, which include the police, provincial government and Alotau authorities, from taking any step whatsoever to evict or repatriate any of the plaintiffs from their current homes. “Threatening, harassing and intimidating in whatsoever manner the plaintiffs and their families” was also restrained. Also, the defendants are restrained from entering the homes and premises of the plaintiffs to evict or repatriate the plaintiffs in the absence of any orders or warrants issued by a court of competent jurisdiction. The matter is adjourned to Tuesday July 6 for inter partes hearing. The order takes place forthwith. The plaintiffs acting on behalf of the settlers are Steven Paul Nesai, Paulus Mumna and Steven Luguna, who are represented by Baniyamai Lawyers.     ', NULL, NULL),
(201, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/hong-kong-police-arrests-apple-daily-newspaper-editor-in-chief/', 'World News', ' Hong Kong police arrests Apple Daily newspaper editor-in-chief ', '   HONG KONG: Hong Kong’s national security police have arrested the editor-in-chief and four other directors of the Apple Daily newspaper in early morning raids involving hundreds of officers, over their role in the publication of dozens of articles alleged to be part of a conspiracy to collude with foreign forces. The city’s security chief, John Lee, accused those arrested of using “journalistic work as a tool to endanger national security”, and issued a chilling warning to residents and other media. “Normal journalists are different from these people,” Lee said. “Please keep a distance from them.” The police force’s national security department said the five had been arrested on suspicion of collusion with a foreign country or with external elements to endanger national security, through articles which police said called for sanctions to be imposed on Hong Kong and mainland China. All were arrested at their homes, at around 7am. Police also searched Apple Daily’s newsroom and its offices, saying the warrant covered “the power of searching and seizure of journalistic materials”. “The operation, still ongoing, aims at gathering evidence for a case of suspected contravention of the national security law,” it said. Those arrested were named by Apple Daily as editor-in-chief, Ryan Law; the chief executive officer, Cheung Kim-hung; the chief operating officer, Chow Tat-kuen; the deputy chief editor, Chan Puiman; and the chief executive editor, Cheung Chi-wai. Police also froze HK$18m (US $2.3m) in assets of three companies, Apple Daily Limited, Apple Daily Printing Limited and AD Internet Limited. Parent company, Next Digital, announced the suspension of trading in its shares before markets opened on Thursday. The police operation is a significant escalation in the government’s moves to stifle Hong Kong’s press, of which the pro-democracy tabloid was widely considered to be a primary target. Senior superintendent Steve Li Kwai-wah, the head of the police’s national security division, said there was “very strong evidence that the questionable articles played a very crucial part in the conspiracy, which provided ammunition for foreign countries, institutions and organisations to impose sanctions”, adding that those arrested played “a very important role” in their publication. -The Guardian   ', NULL, NULL),
(202, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/pm-to-launch-alternative-highlands-highway/', 'National News', ' PM to launch alternative Highlands Highway ', '   BY ISAAC LIRI THE 64km Dunantina-Ramu Highway in Kesavaka, Henganofi district of Eastern Highlands Province was announced yesterday as an alternate Highlands Highway. The road once completed in the future will give options to travellers coming from the upper Highlands and those coming from the coastal provinces of Madang and Morobe to take the route. The launch was officiated by Prime Minister James Marape, Works Minister Michael Nali, Minister for National Planning and Monitoring Renbo Paita, Eastern Highlands Governor Peter Numu, Henganofi MP Robert Atiyafa, Mining Minister Johnson Tuke, Minister for Petroleum Saki Soloma, Goroka MP Aiye Tambua, Works Secretary David Wereh and others. Hundreds both young and old gathered at Kesavakato witness what was described as a historical event to hear the government talk of how the road will benefit the people of Henganofi and the Highlands and Momase regions. Mr Marape told the people of Kesavaka constructing roads is a priority in which his government has embarked on therefore, commended Mr Atiyafa for working tirelessly to see that the project proceeds. He said the government through the Works Department have been working on roads under a program which he referred to as Connect PNG with the aim of connecting parts of country especially in rural areas with roads. He also added that the government is spending billions on constructing and maintaining roads.
Therefore the people must allow development to take place because the road will benefit them now and in the future. Mr Nali also encouraged the people of Henganofi to change their mindsets and prepare to welcome the development of the road. He said under the Asian Development Bank, the Dunantina-Ramu road will proceed on as trench one meaning that the project implementation is just around the corner. Both Mr Numu and Mr Atiyafa thanked the Prime Minister and State Ministers for visiting Dunantina and they described the place once known as back page to become a front page meaning that business activities and other government services such as health and education will flourish following the opening of the alternate highway.   ', NULL, NULL),
(203, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/air-niugini-flights-to-cairns-still-suspended/', 'Business', ' Air Niugini flights to Cairns still suspended ', '   The Australian government has extended the suspension of international arrivals into Cairns until end of this month. This is in order to manage the risk of arriving passengers subsequently testing positive for COVID-19 during their stay in quarantine facilities. For the period from June 19- 30, flights from PNG to Cairns have therefore been cancelled. Passengers holding tickets for Cairns flights over this period should contact Air Niugini or their travel agent for rebooking options. Air Niugini continues to operate six services a week to Brisbane, and a weekly service to Sydney. Air Niugini regrets the inconvenience caused and appreciates its customers’ patience and understanding while it manages its way through these latest border restrictions.   ', NULL, NULL),
