(205, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/by-election-quality-checks-put-on-hold/', 'Top Stories', ' By-election quality checks put on hold ', '   BY THIERRY LEPANI Quality checks of the first preference votes counted at the various wards continues to drag on through the week after officials and scrutineers finally got their brief yesterday at the Sir John Guise stadium by officials. The quality checks were supposed to start at 2pm yesterday, however difficulties with ensuring counting officials were identified resulted in police going through the task of calling names of officials and checking identification. Shortly after, scrutineers on site refused to participate after news of a purported petition by a number of candidates outlining grievances was to be presented to the Returning Officer. After some time, the scrutineers came to a compromise and one-by-one entered the premises under the supervision of police to get briefed on the quality checks. Electoral officials then gathered the counting officials and scrutineers in the counting centre and gave them a rundown of the quality checks process. An official explained that the container with the ward 11 ballot boxes would be the first to undergo quality checks. The official said after the quality checks are completed, the progressive scores will be confirmed before heading to elimination. Officials were made aware that the criteria for an invalid ballot must be double checked on all ballots – ensuring the correct name of the candidate for the appropriate box is indicated. Quality checks for the different wards are set to progress today; however, almost certain it will be marred with delays and confusion.   ', NULL, NULL),
(206, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/png-needs-more-banks-pidik/', 'Business', ' PNG needs more banks: Pidik ', '   BY MAXINE KAMUS More commercial banks are needed in Papua New Guinea, says Bank of PNG assistant governor Ellison Pidik. Mr Pidik said as PNG is an emerging economy with a growing population and a market that is expanding at a faster rate than ever before, these indicates that PNG needs new players to enter into the banking space. He said in order to have balance in the market BPNG is welcoming other banks from overseas to come and operate and provide service to the growing population. “PNG banking space needs balance, it needs international banks to enter and operate in the country as currently we have four major banks that are operating at the commercial level,” Mr Pidik said. “We have four commercial banks in PNG financial sector with other deposit taking institutes that include 21 savings and loan societies and 10 licensed financial institutions. “With BSP as the largest in the country with 35 branches throughout the country and in six countries, BSP currently services over 650,000 business banking customers and with our fast growing population the banking sector needs more banks to enter,” Mr Pidik said. He said PNG needs banks that are listed on the stock exchanges, like Kina Bank and BSP who was recently listed on the stock exchanges in Australia. This is good as both are local and international banks although they are both domicile locally. Mr Pidik said the central bank is now looking at investors around the world and is also inviting other financial institutions operating to look at how they can merge something bigger that can qualify for a banking license similar to what the Teachers Savings and Loan Society (TISA) has done to apply for a banking license to operate as a commercial bank. He said TISA has applied specifically for a commercial banking license, which BPNG has assessed and identified a number of important priorities that BPNG thinks TISA should look into before BPNG go through completing the assessment of the license. Mr Pidik said, BPNG has met with the board and management of TISA and asked them to look into areas like prerequisites that they have to have in place before the assessment will be completed.   ', NULL, NULL),
(207, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/thoughts-of-jokadi-to-inspire-hunters-this-weekend/', 'Sports', ' Thoughts of Jokadi to inspire Hunters this weekend ', '   SP PNG Hunters will play for their teammate Jokadi Bire when they step into an NRL arena for Sunday’s much-awaited Intrust Super Cup clash with Burleigh Bears. The game will be played at Cbus Super Stadium on the Gold Coast as a curtain-raiser to the NRL clash between the Titans and Manly Sea Eagles. The Hunters would have loved Bire to have joined them in the backline however he will be at a Gold Coast hospital where he continues to recover from surgery on Tuesday night. Bire would not be out of place in the NRL arena with the fast feet and power that brought him a try in last Saturday’s clash with Norths Devils at Bishop Park. He flashed off his left foot and surged past Broncos hooker Danny Levi for an important try. Bire’s position in Sunday’s team will be taken by Norman Brown, who has overcome injury and moves from fullback to centre, while captain Ila Alu has recovered from a head knock to take his place. Hunters coach Matt Church said the two changes were another sign of the stability returning to selections in time for the second half of the season. “We’ve had to make two changes this week but otherwise we’re happy to have a very similar team to last week as we continue to build combinations for this run towards the finals,” Church said. “It’s a thrill for our guys to play at this ground. Most of our players fell in love with the game crowded around a TV with villages full of people watching on. Every kid in PNG wishes to play in the stadiums where their heroes play.” This will be the Hunters’ first game at Cbus Super Stadium although Kumuls Wartovo Puara Jnr and Stanton Albert represented their country on the ground against Fiji in 2015. Luke Page also represented the Kumuls in that match but he will lead Burleigh on Sunday in only their second match at the ground – the Bears defeated the Tigers there in 2018. The Hunters have established a close rivalry with the Bears, winning seven of their 13 previous matches. They were on track for an eighth win in April this year before the Bears ran home late to claim a memorable Kokoda Cup clash at Pizzey Park. The Hunters are determined to win on Sunday before a mid-season bye ends another block of matches in this season’s competition. After the bye, the Hunters will have three consecutive games before one last week off before the run to the finals. The Hunters are on the verge of a big performance after testing heavyweights such as Norths, Redcliffe and Townsville Blackhawks in recent weeks with the enterprising play that has rivals on notice. Solo Wane’s length-of-the-field run last Saturday was among the highlights of the round, leaving the Devils in his wake as he scorched 100m down the sideline for a stirring try. The SP PNG Hunters to play Burleigh Bears at Cbus Super Stadium on Sunday June 20 at 1.30pm:  SP PNG HUNTERS: 1. Joe Joshua 2. Junior Rau. 3.Brandon Nima. 4. Norman Brown. 5. Solo Wane. 6. Ase Boas 7 Charlie Simon. 8. Stanton Albert. 9. Wartovo Puara Jnr. 10. Samuel Yegip 11. Emmanuel Waine 12. Keven Appo. 13. Ila Alu (c). Interchange: 14. Judah Rimbu. 15. Sylvester Namo 16. Mark Piti 17. Enock Maki. Coach: Matt Church. BURLEIGH BEARS: 1. Kurtis Rowe 2. Jonus Pearson. 3. Conor Carey 4. Allan Lockwood 5. Andre Niko 6. Tanah Boyd 7. Conner Toia 8. Luke Page 9. Pat Politoni 10. John Palavi 11. Lochlyn Sheldon 12. Hayden Schwass. 13. Sam Coster. Interchange: 14. Shallin Fuller 15. Reece Summer 16. Api Noema-Matenga. 17.  Jeff Lynch. Coach: Rick Stone. Match officials: Liam Kennedy, Jarrod Cole, Steve Kanowski.         ', NULL, NULL),
