(209, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/biden-and-putin-praise-geneva-summit-talks-but-discord-remains/', 'World News', ' Biden and Putin praise Geneva summit talks but discord remains ', '   WASHINGTON: The presidents of the US and Russia have praised their talks in Geneva but have made little concrete progress at the first such meeting since 2018. Disagreements were stated, said US President Joe Biden, but not in a hyperbolic way, and he said Russia did not want a new Cold War. Russian President Vladimir Putin said Mr Biden was an experienced statesman and the two “spoke the same language”. The talks lasted around three hours, less time than was scheduled. Mr Biden said they did not need to spend more time talking and there was now a genuine prospect to improve relations with Russia. As a gift to the Russian leader, Mr Biden brought Mr Putin a custom-made pair of aviator sunglasses, a style favoured by the US president, and a crystal sculpture of a bison. It is unclear whether Mr Putin gave Mr Biden a gift. In 2018, the Russian leader gave former President Donald Trump a soccer ball after a meeting in Helsinki, Finland. The two sides agreed to begin a dialogue on nuclear arms control. They also said they would return ambassadors to each other’s capitals – the envoys were mutually withdrawn for consultations in March, after the US accused Russia of meddling in the 2020 presidential election. However, there was little sign of agreement on other issues, including cyber-security, Ukraine and the fate of Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny, who is currently serving a two-and-a-half-year sentence in a penal colony. Mr Biden said there would be “devastating consequences” for Russia if Navalny died in prison. Mr Putin hinted at a possible deal on exchanging prisoners, saying he believed compromises could be found. – BBC   ', NULL, NULL),
(210, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/solomon-cup-attracts-50-teams-in-bialla/', 'Sports', ' Solomon Cup attracts 50 teams in Bialla ', '   Local resident in Bialla town West New Britain Andrew Solomon has pledged K50,000 for Solomon Cup which will run for 20 weeks as soccer (male teams – 18 & female teams – 12) and volleyball (eight male teams and 12 female teams) competition. Solomon said at this time when law and order issues are at its highest peak in West New Britain, he pledged his support to the youths (boys and girls) in Bialla town with these competitions. He said Bialla has created history and has potential to produce super stars like Marcus Bai in rugby league. He said he will officiate at another competition around July in Kabaiya LSS, Noau village, Lolobau Island, Silanga, Marapu and Ubai village in Bialla LLG with a similar financial support before moving into Mosa LLG, Hoskins LLG, Kimbe Urban LLG, Talasea LLG and Bali Witu LLG. Rugby league will soon start in all local level governments too. He met with Sports Minister Wesley Raminai last week to deliver an official invitation to officiate at the Solomon Cup grand finals in October and is expected to be accompanied by PNG Football Association president, PNG Volleyball Association president, PNGRFL chairman and PNG Sports Federation chief executive officer. There will also be a district games that will see sides selected from each LLG to compete for K200,000 in various sports. He said his priority games are rugby league, soccer, volleyball and basketball and developing raw talent onto professionals. He said his main focus is to support Team West New Britain prepare for PNG Games in Mendi, Southern Highlands Province that is expected to be held in November this year.     ', NULL, NULL),
(211, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/five-athletes-join-team-png-for-the-tokyo-olympics/', 'Sports', ' Five Athletes join Team PNG for the Tokyo Olympics ', '   With less than forty days to the opening ceremony of the Tokyo Olympic Games, five more athletes have been confirmed to represent Team PNG next month. With the two Sailing, siblings of Teariki Numa and Rose-Lee Numa already qualified, that brings seven athletes confirmed to attend the Olympic Games in Tokyo from 23 July to 8 August 2021. The latest athletes to be confirmed include Weightlifters Dika Toua and Morea Baru, lone Papua New Guinea (PNG) Boxing contender John Ume along with Swimmers Judith Meauri and Ryan Maskelyne. PNG’s veteran weightlifter and Commonwealth gold medalist, Dika Toua secured her place on merit and willcreate history by being the first female Weightlifter to participate at five (5)Olympic Games. Fellow Weightlifter and Commonwealth Games Silver medalist, Morea Baru also qualified on merit through the Oceania continental placing. Both were the top ranked athletes in their respective categories in the Oceania region when the qualification period ended on 11 June 2021. Dika will be competing in the Women’s 49kg division and is scheduled to compete on Saturday 24 July whilst Morea will be competing on Sunday 25 July in the Men’s 61kg division. Both are currently in training under their longtime coach Paul Coffa’ at the new Oceania Weightlifting Institute in Melbourne, since leaving PNG in May this year. Weightlifting is now the second PNG sport to have qualified their athletes through the continental quota, apart from sailing which already have PNG sibling sailors Te’Ariki and Rose Numa-Leewho will be competing in the Men’s Laser and Women’s Laser Radial events respectively at the Olympics. The Laser competition will take place out at the Enoshima Yacht Harbor beginning on Sunday 25 July, and will have five race days before the final on 1 August 2021. PNG’s Boxing contender and Pacific Games Gold Medalist, John Ume is the fifth athlete to have been confirmed this week after he was offered a tripartite invitation place to participate at the Tokyo Olympic Games in the Men’s Light (57-63kg) weight division. Tripartite invitation places are only offered to certain individual sports and events (one per event) and is only available to ninety-two other National Olympic Committees of which PNG is one. The International Olympic Committee Tripartite Commission in consultation with the respective International Federations makes the decision on who will be offered a tripartite invitation place based on past performances. Swimming also confirmed their two athletes to take up the Universality Placings with current Olympian Judith Meauri selected for the female universality place and Ryan Maskelyne selected for the male universality place. Universality places are offered to National Olympic Committee’s (NOC) that do not have athletes qualify on merit. Meauriwill compete in the women’s 50m freestyle event and is currently on a Fédération internationale de natation (FINA) swimming scholarship in Thailand, and will travel directly to Tokyo from Thailand. She is scheduled to swim on Friday 30 July. Maskelyne will become the latest Olympian and he will compete in the Men’s 200m Breaststroke on Tuesday 27 July. He is currently based in Brisbane, Australia and recently competed in the Australian Olympic Swim Trials where he finished 9th clocking 2:17.14 Athletics will have one athlete be part of Team PNG through the Universality Placing and it is a tight race between Toea Wisil and Rellie Kaputin. Wisil is currently competing in USA and will be looking to improve on her recent times in the 100m whilst Kaputin who is based in Australia will also be looking to improve on her jumps this week in the Long Jump event. Athletics PNG will confirm their selected athlete for the Universality Place based on the top ranked athlete on the World Athletics World Rankings as per their selection criteria. Currently in Monacoto participate in the Women’s World Rugby Sevens Repechage tournament from 19-20 June are the PNG Rugby 7s Women Team who will be looking to string some strong performances to advance past the pool stages. The PNG Rugby 7s Women’s team are optimistic of their chances to make it to the final and finish in the top two out of twelve nations to qualify for the Tokyo 2020 Olympic Games. A proud Team PNG’s Chef de Mission Tamzin Wardley to the Tokyo 2020 Olympics congratulated the Weightlifters for qualifying on merit as well as John Ume, Ryan Maskelyne and Judith Meauri who were granted tripartite invitation place and universality places respectively.           ', NULL, NULL),
(212, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/wnb-government-partners-with-chamber-of-commerce/', 'National News', ' WNB government partners with Chamber of Commerce ', '   By NICOLE JOANNES The West New Britain Provincial Government is partnering with the Chamber of Commerce and Industry for the use of PSIP funds allocated to Kimbe police. They have entered a memorandum of agreement for the Chamber of Commerce to disburse the funds to service providers upon submissions presented by the police. The agreement provides the guidelines for the use of the K500,000 presented to chamber by the regional Member Sasindran Muthuvel. This agreement was signed by Provincial Administrator Williamson Hosea, President of the Chamber of Commerce and Industry Ian O’Hanlon and provincial police commander Januarius Vosivai. The focus areas for the funding include the maintenance of the ten new vehicles and firearms, information call centre setup, community policing and other operational areas like CID, intelligence, VHF radios and infrastructures among others. Mr Muthuvel said this will save police time to have access to the money instead of the long government process. He thanked the Chamber of Commerce for the partnership arrangement which has also gone down well with the police. Mr Muthuvel said this arrangement came about following the visit of Lands Minister and Member for Lae John Rosso last year. Mr Rosso had an audience with chamber, and they had agreed for this move to cut down on time and to improve the response time of the police that is aimed at improving law and order. Meanwhile the acting assistant commissioner of police for NGI Paul Kamuai has thanked the provincial government and the Chamber of Commerce for this partnership arrangement. He also thanked the MP for the funding assistance and assured that the money will be used for the intended purposes to improve law and order in the province. Mr Kamuai said the expenditure on the use of the funding will be provided by PPC Vosivai.   ', NULL, NULL),
(213, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/bodies-of-20-suspected-illegal-miners-found/', 'World News', ' Bodies of 20 suspected illegal miners found ', '   CAPE TOWN: Police in South Africa have discovered the bodies of 20 suspected illegal miners near an abandoned goldmine shaft south-west of Johannesburg. Police said in a statement they were investigating the cause of the deaths, adding that the men’s bodies “were found wrapped in white plastic bags” and bore “severe body burns”. “All the deceased are suspected to be illegal miners commonly known as ‘zama zamas’ operating in obsolete shafts in Orkney and Stilfontein,” just under 200km (125 miles) south-west of Johannesburg, police said in the statement. Thousands of “zama zamas” – which means “those who try their luck” in Zulu – operate in the country, according to the South African Human Rights Commission (SAHRC). Most are in Johannesburg, South Africa’s commercial capital, which is built on some of the world’s richest gold deposits. The first five bodies were discovered on Monday and 15 more on Tuesday, police spokesperson Brigadier Sabata Mokgwabone told AFP on Wednesday. The first group was found outside a disused mine shaft, local media reported. Fourteen more “decomposed bodies were found along Ariston Road near the railway line,” police spokesperson Brig Sabata Mokgwabone told the Sunday Times. Most illegal mining is run by crime syndicates. A 2018 report by the Global Initiative Against Transnational Organized Crime estimated that it costs South Africa more than £753m a year. The practice is extremely dangerous, with the risk of injuries and deaths from explosives, toxic fume inhalation, collapsing mine shafts and gang violence. – BBC   ', NULL, NULL),
(214, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/empower-women/', 'National News', ' ‘Empower women’ ', '   BY PATRICK TOM WOMEN play important role in the community and they deserve to be supported in any way possible to empower them. Australia High Commissioner to Papua New Guinea Jon Philp says the roles women play in their respective families and communities entitle them to be given a voice to stand up and participate in the community. Mr Philp told the women group during the financial literacy 16th graduation that they (women) are important and should be given the power of choice to participate in any decision making and be part of the community. “Women are a manager of the family, and house thus it’s important that we give every woman in our society the opportunity to participate,” he said. “For the children to be better educated it comes back to how educated the mothers are and this helps empower the family, community and society as whole.”
He said PNG needs women leaders and it is time we give equal opportunity to women to take the country forward. NCDC Women Commissioner Elice Siki urges the women to take every opportunity in whatever things they are venturing in to empower their family, clan and society. She said on behalf of all the women, she acknowledges the presence of the Australian High Commissioner Jon Philp for attending their graduation and presenting them the certificates. “Women are vital part of community development and I represent all the women in the city and this gives me great pleasure to see what these women are undergoing, the basic financial literacy training,”   ', NULL, NULL),
(215, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/court-order-stops-eviction-of-alotau-settlers/', 'Latest News', ' Court order stops eviction of Alotau settlers ', '   BY THIERRY LEPANI A COURT order has been successfully obtained to stop the eviction of residents of the 26 different settlements, compounds and villages in Alotau. The National Court order was handed down yesterday by Justice Collin Makail which stays the eviction exercise currently underway pending the determination of the substantive matter. The order states “The current eviction and repatriation exercise being under taken by the Defendants and their agents and employees in and around Alotau town is stayed or injuncted. “Any direction instruction, and orders by the First, Second and Third Defendants to repatriate or evict the plaintiffs and others from their current homes in the 26 settlements, compounds and villages  is stayed or injuncted”. The 26 affected settlements concerned are: Power House/AOG Habours Rabaraba Goodenough Watertank Goilanai (Customary Land) Gawa Hideaway Duau Mobil/IPL 1 Mobil/IPL 2 Kewa Yabwau PTB NBC Red Hill Denewa (Customary Land) Kuboma Masurina Niugini Kitava (Customary Land) Siona 1 and 2 (Customary Land) Musa (Customary Land) Suau (Customary Land) Daga (Customary Land) Morima KB (Customary Land) Hihiyaola (customary land) Justice Makail also ordered that the defendants, which include the police, provincial government and Alotau authorities, from taking any step whatsoever to evict or repatriate any of the plaintiffs from their current homes. “Threatening, harassing and intimidating in whatsoever manner the plaintiffs and their families” was also restrained. Also, the defendants are restrained from entering the homes and premises of the plaintiffs to evict or repatriate the plaintiffs in the absence of any orders or warrants issued by a court of competent jurisdiction. The matter is adjourned to Tuesday July 6 for inter partes hearing. The order takes place forthwith. The plaintiffs acting on behalf of the settlers are Steven Paul Nesai, Paulus Mumna and Steven Luguna, who are represented by Baniyamai Lawyers.     ', NULL, NULL),
(216, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/pm-to-launch-alternative-highlands-highway/', 'National News', ' PM to launch alternative Highlands Highway ', '   BY ISAAC LIRI THE 64km Dunantina-Ramu Highway in Kesavaka, Henganofi district of Eastern Highlands Province was announced yesterday as an alternate Highlands Highway. The road once completed in the future will give options to travellers coming from the upper Highlands and those coming from the coastal provinces of Madang and Morobe to take the route. The launch was officiated by Prime Minister James Marape, Works Minister Michael Nali, Minister for National Planning and Monitoring Renbo Paita, Eastern Highlands Governor Peter Numu, Henganofi MP Robert Atiyafa, Mining Minister Johnson Tuke, Minister for Petroleum Saki Soloma, Goroka MP Aiye Tambua, Works Secretary David Wereh and others. Hundreds both young and old gathered at Kesavakato witness what was described as a historical event to hear the government talk of how the road will benefit the people of Henganofi and the Highlands and Momase regions. Mr Marape told the people of Kesavaka constructing roads is a priority in which his government has embarked on therefore, commended Mr Atiyafa for working tirelessly to see that the project proceeds. He said the government through the Works Department have been working on roads under a program which he referred to as Connect PNG with the aim of connecting parts of country especially in rural areas with roads. He also added that the government is spending billions on constructing and maintaining roads.
Therefore the people must allow development to take place because the road will benefit them now and in the future. Mr Nali also encouraged the people of Henganofi to change their mindsets and prepare to welcome the development of the road. He said under the Asian Development Bank, the Dunantina-Ramu road will proceed on as trench one meaning that the project implementation is just around the corner. Both Mr Numu and Mr Atiyafa thanked the Prime Minister and State Ministers for visiting Dunantina and they described the place once known as back page to become a front page meaning that business activities and other government services such as health and education will flourish following the opening of the alternate highway.   ', NULL, NULL),
(217, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/by-election-quality-checks-put-on-hold/', 'Top Stories', ' By-election quality checks put on hold ', '   BY THIERRY LEPANI Quality checks of the first preference votes counted at the various wards continues to drag on through the week after officials and scrutineers finally got their brief yesterday at the Sir John Guise stadium by officials. The quality checks were supposed to start at 2pm yesterday, however difficulties with ensuring counting officials were identified resulted in police going through the task of calling names of officials and checking identification. Shortly after, scrutineers on site refused to participate after news of a purported petition by a number of candidates outlining grievances was to be presented to the Returning Officer. After some time, the scrutineers came to a compromise and one-by-one entered the premises under the supervision of police to get briefed on the quality checks. Electoral officials then gathered the counting officials and scrutineers in the counting centre and gave them a rundown of the quality checks process. An official explained that the container with the ward 11 ballot boxes would be the first to undergo quality checks. The official said after the quality checks are completed, the progressive scores will be confirmed before heading to elimination. Officials were made aware that the criteria for an invalid ballot must be double checked on all ballots – ensuring the correct name of the candidate for the appropriate box is indicated. Quality checks for the different wards are set to progress today; however, almost certain it will be marred with delays and confusion.   ', NULL, NULL),
(218, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/ela-motors-opens-new-dealership/', 'Business', ' Ela Motors opens new dealership ', '   BY JANET KARI Ela Motors branch in Lae has opened its newest dealership at Malaita Street in town early this week. The new dealership contains a spacious showroom, an office space for sales and administration, a customer service section for spare parts, a large workshop, and service area for car wash, an adequate parking space and others. This new set up is specifically for the franchise of Toyota which includes Toyota vehicles, spare parts for this franchise and a large workshop specifically for the Toyota brand, while the other dealership at Milford Haven road deals with Yamaha and Hino. The new shop now adds to the current ones operating at Taraka and at Milford Haven Road, with most of its customer services areas set up in a COVID-19 protective manner.   ', NULL, NULL),
(219, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/probe-into-pmiz-financing/', 'Top Stories', ' Probe into PMIZ financing ', '   Treasurer Ian Ling-Stuckey has announced a new study aimed at resuming work on the long-delayed Pacific Maritime Industrial Zone project in Madang. PMIZ has been a white elephant sitting on the fringes of reality since 2004 by past and present governments. When the then O’Neill government officially launched the project in 2015, it was touted to be the start of a US$95 million construction phase, saying then that it will earn the country between US$2 and US$4 billion (K7 billion and K14 billion) a year, once fully developed. The Treasurer’s announcement follows talks with Fisheries Minister, Dr Lino Tom and Justice Minister and Madang MP Bryan Kramer. Mr Ling-Stuckey said his visit to Madang was part of the government’s review of the Medium Term Revenue Strategy (MTRS) for 2023-2027. The study is to identify potential new sources of finance for the project, discover the whereabouts of more than K300 million previously committed to it, and investigate dubious land dealings. A point the local Member Mr Kramer raised was that despite the loan being drawn down, and substantial PNG counterpart funding of more than K50 million being spent, all that exists is a half-built entrance, dilapidated staff housing and rusty fencing. The project, which has been under the control of various departments and agencies since it was first promoted about 20 years ago, was transferred back to the National Fisheries Authority by a NEC decision this month. “Recent work by government agencies has cleared up some technical and financial concerns about the project, and reaffirmed its fundamental attraction,” Mr Ling-Stuckey highlighted. “The economic and industrial underpinnings of the project are well-known, and well-founded, and the government is enthusiastic about its prospects. But more work is required to bring it to fruition, hence this study.” Mr Ling-Stuckey said the project envisages up to 10 tuna factories, advanced port and wharf facilities including a container terminal, a tuna auction centre, new roads and new drainage and wastewater systems, a communications hub and a new office complex. “It is expected that up to 30,000 jobs and hundreds of spin-off opportunities could be created.” A 2016 study conducted by State-owned Kumul Consolidated Holdings estimated that an expanded project would cost about $US156 million (K547m). He said Minister Tom has raised the possible resumption of the project with the Ministerial Economic Committee, and conducted a site visit and briefing for the Treasurer and Mr Kramer. The project was originally funded by a $US95 million loan from China Exim Bank and counterpart PNG funding. The loan is still being paid off, and there is an outstanding debt to the bank of K42.6 million. “The scope of the project is of significance not only to Madang and the Momase region, but to the nation. “ Mr Ling-Stuckey said the Government wants to see it proceed in a responsible, transparent and accountable way.   ', NULL, NULL),
