(225, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/counting-for-ward-8-and-11-begins/', 'Latest News', ' Counting for Ward 8 and 11 begins ', '   BY REBECCA KUKU Counting for Ward 8 and 11 at the Sir John Guise Stadium has begun with three ballot boxes from each of the two containers. Returning Officer for Moresby North-West Desmond Timiyaso said that they had a slow start but he was hoping to complete the Primary Count by Saturday this week. “But for Ward 8, its a small ward so we should complete the Primary Count by Friday,” he said. Meanwhile, counting at Ward 1 and Ward 10 has also started with police personnel on site at all wards.     ', NULL, NULL),
(226, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/sinai-no-by-election-for-kerema-open-seat/', 'Top Stories', ' Sinai: No by-election for Kerema Open seat ', '   BY REBECCA KUKU There will be no by-election for the Kerema Open seat says acting Electoral Commissioner Simon Sinai. He said there will be no more by-elections after July 24. “We are fast running out of time, and the cut off time for any by-election is July 24, which is when all writs for any by-election are always returned. “We are already also into preparing for the 2022 National General Election, so this current Moresby Northwest by-election will be the last one,” he said. A concerned Gulf son, Thomas Opa, who was the second runner-up for the Kerema open seat in 2017, said that under the Constitution, it provides for a by-election to take place in the event of the death of the sitting MP and with over 12 months left before the next return of writs. “It is only fair that the people of Kerema district are represented in Parliament even when the time is short. This is because the Constitution provides for this. “However, it has dragged on and on and now time has caught up and now time factor is used as an excuse to not conduct a by-election, thus depriving the people of Kerema. “It is quite sad that the people of Kerema will have no representation and voice in Parliament for the remainder of this term of Parliament. “But I can’t say much as we must respect the decision of the PNG Electoral Commissioner Mr Simon Sinai to not conduct a by-election for the Kerema Open seat,” he said. Mr Opa said the people of Kerema were resilient people and will humbly accept the decision as they prepare and look forward to the 2022 National General Election to find a replacement for late MP Richard Mendani.   ', NULL, NULL),
(227, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/allowances-to-be-paid-next-week/', 'Latest News', ' Allowances to be paid next week ', '   BY REBECCA KUKU  Police personnel for the Moresby North-West by-election will have their allowances paid next week. NCD Metropolitan Chief Gideon Ikumu told Post-Courier that the Police Headquarters had released a cheque of K500, 000 yesterday and this would require a three day clearance. “Due to the by-election funding not being released yet, the police headquarters has agreed to give the K500, 000 from police funds to sort the allowances of policemen and women with the understanding that when the funds are later released the K500, 000 will go back to the headquarters.” “The money once cleared, will be used to pay out allowances for the policemen and women at the counting sites so that counting can continue. All the others will be sorted afterwards as well, but we will start with the ones at counting.” “Allowances will be paid in various forms, some for seven days, some for 14 days, whilst the ones providing security will be 21 days and so forth.” “But we will sort them next week,” he said. Mr Ikumu said that he will be addressing the police now for counting to resume. However, from reliable sources in the constabulary, policemen and women do not want to continue working until their allowances are paid due to past experiences, claiming that the government still owed them allowances from past elections and other operations.       ', NULL, NULL),
(228, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/pm-basil-to-launch-projects/', 'Top Stories', ' PM, Basil to launch projects ', '   BY SAMPSON BONAI Prime Minister James Marape will travel to Bulolo to launch the road projects in Wau and Buang LLG today. He will be accompanied by Deputy Prime Minister and Bulolo MP Sam Basil. Bulolo district project officer Mona Clyde confirmed Mr Marape’s trip to the district to launch the various projects and said a program had been finalised for the launching. Wau/Bulolo Urban LLG town mayor Willie Sine travelled to Lae to finalise the launching program with Mr Clyde and said the program has been confirmed for today. “We are looking forward to hosting Prime Minister James Marape and Deputy Prime Minister and Bulolo MP Sam Basil to the historical mining town of Wau, ” Mr Sine said. “The organising committee with the help of the communities has cleaned up the sporting field and other parts of town to host the important gathering.” He added that the school children and women’s group will participate in the welcoming program when he arrived at the airstrip. A big delegation including a media contingent will accompany the Mr Marape and Mr Basil on the trip to witness the launching of the project.   ', NULL, NULL),
(229, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/funding-needed-to-plan-for-2022-polls/', 'Top Stories', ' Funding needed to plan for 2022 polls ', '   Acting Deputy Police Commissioner Donald Yamasombi has expressed gratitude for the good turnout at the second meeting for the 2022 National Election security committee. He said the meeting, held at the Police Operation Center (POC) at Konedobu in Port Moresby last Thursday, was a positive indication that stakeholders like police, PNG Defence Force, Correctional Services and Electoral Commission (PNGEC) were serious and concerned for a free and fair 2022 National General Elections. “And for the first time since 1975, we have the health experts like the St John Ambulances Services joining us due to the presence of COVID-19.” Mr Yamasombi said the outcome of the meeting had all the stakeholders contributing their respective pre-planning stages with the police presenting a powerpoint presentation on Police Commissioner’s intent on how joint forces security should assist PNGEC to deliver Election 2022. “However, the committee has expressed concern that their respective plans will be successful only if the National Government provided the required funds as soon as possible as elections are just less than 10 months away and the electoral roll update was planned for July 2021. “And that exercise also depends on funding. “Also the tentative dates for election have not been made known as yet.” Mr Yamasombi said the PNGEC had submitted a letter to the Governor-General and is yet to receive a response. “We need the dates and also funding to plan now to collect intelligence to properly plan our operations. “We (police) critically need to collect and analyse security threats and resources in all the provinces and funding is priority to install appropriate personnel in all the provinces to gather this information. And time is of the essence. “Also we are concerned of traditionally peaceful provinces like Milne Bay and Madang, which are experiencing extreme violent criminal activities. We are concerned of the Highlands region, which traditionally is always the hotspot areas for our security planning,” he said. The committee also expressed concern to prepare for logistics purposes such as procuring vehicles, planning to engage aircrafts like helicopters and boats to be used for the transportation of ballot boxes, polling and security personnel to polling areas throughout the country.   ', NULL, NULL),
(230, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/powi-hits-back-at-defamatory-talks/', 'Top Stories', ' Powi hits back at defamatory talks ', '   Southern Highlands Governor William Powi says he will sue leaders who destroy his reputation and called him names at a recent political rally in the Southern Highlands. Speaking during a media conference yesterday, he said footage of speeches destroying his reputation and name calling indicated that there were evidence of his reputation being tarnished and he has instructed his lawyers to study the footage and institute criminal proceedings against those involved. Mr Powi was relating to comments made by former prime minister and member for Ialibu-Pangia Peter O’Neill and other leaders who spoke during a political rally at Map village near Mendi in the Southern Highlands last Friday. He condemned the political rally conducted and orchestrated by the Peoples National Congress (PNC) led by Mr O’Neill, current and failed politicians which could have been mindful of section 148 of the Organic Law on election that prohibits political rallies and early campaigning. He said during the rally, some leaders made defamatory statements of his character and he will test it in court and had advised his lawyers to have it presented to the courts. “Leaders must be responsible of their actions,” he said. “If they differ then they must differ in policies and the way you believe in issues. “They have gone too low in character assassination. “I have instructed my lawyers to take the matter to court. “The video footages are very clear, I will not let this statements be unchallenged, so we stop this nonsense of leaders destroying another leader’s character. “If you have differences, face me in 2022 as much as I will face you and that is the right avenue. “On that note, I’m appealing to the member for Ialibu-Pangia not to use young men I have built as proxy to play dirty politics of deceitful nature, politics of conniving, stagey and making us fight each other in SHP and we had enough of this nonsense so I’m appealing to him to do the right thing and allow the people of SHP to choose between you and me come 2022 as a regional candidate and do not use proxies that I have raised to come and put up a challenge.” He said for the defamatory remarks, the competent court will decide if there is any element of them assassinating his character and called names like crocodile so that leaders in the future can be held accountable for their actions. “Crocodiles are very tough animals but I do not have swamps in SHP for crocodiles to live and breed,” he said.   ', NULL, NULL),
(231, 2, 2, '2021-06-19 00:00:00', 'https://postcourier.com.pg/ballot-boxes-disputed-for-moresby-north-west/', 'Latest News', ' Ballot Boxes Disputed for Ward 7 ', '   BY REBECCA KUKU  Candidates have disputed the first count at the Murray Barracks counting venue for Ward 7. Returning Officer for Moresby North-West Desmond Timiyaso told Post-Courier that the counting at Murray Barracks had to be delayed so that  they could address the concerns raised before counting could resume. Mr Timiyaso is heading down to Murray Barracks now to address the concerns.   ', NULL, NULL);

